 behalf of hemophiliacs who were unwittingly infected with tainted blood. As part of the team behind the key class action litigation filed by the infected, young New Jersey lawyer Eric Weinberg was faced with a daunting task: to prove the negligence of a powerful, well-connected global industry worth billions. Weinberg and journalist Donna Shaw tell the dramatic story of how idealistic attorneys and their heroic, mortally-ill clients fought to achieve justice and prevent further infections. A stunning exposé of one of the American medical system's most shameful debacles, Blood on Their Hands is a rousing reminder that, through perseverance, the victims of corporate greed can sometimes achieve great victory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Jan 2021) 0aBiological productsxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aBlood bankszUnited StatesxQuality control. 0aBlood bankszUnited States.xQuality control. 0aBloodxTransfusionxComplicationszUnited States. 0aHemophiliaxLaw and legislationzUnited StatesxCriminal provisions. 0aHemophiliazLaw and legislationxUnited StatesxCriminal provisions. 0aHemophiliacsxInfectionszUnited States. 0aHemophiliacsxLegal status, laws, etczUnited States. 0aHemophiliacsxLegal status, laws, etc.zUnited States. 0aProducts liabilityzUnited States. 4aBig Pharma. 4aHIV. 4ablood. 4abureaucracy. 4aclot. 4agreed. 4ahealth policy. 4ahemophilia. 4ahemophiliac. 4alaw. 4aplasma. 4ashaw. 4aweinberg. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aShaw, Donna, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP eBook-Package 2017z978311066609040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/9780813576244zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813576244423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com